<p><ent>Grip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grip
<hw>Grip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To trench; to drain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Grip
<hw>Grip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>gripe</ets>. Cf.
<er>Grip</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Gripe</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An energetic or tenacious grasp; a holding fast;
strength in grasping.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A peculiar mode of clasping the hand, by which
members of a secret association recognize or greet, one another; <as>as,
a masonic <ex>grip</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That by which anything is grasped; a handle or
gripe; <as>as, the grip of a sword</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A device for grasping or holding fast to
something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Specif., an apparatus attached to a car for
clutching a traction cable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A gripsack; a hand bag; a satchel or suitcase.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The influenza; grippe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Grip
<hw>Grip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Grip</er> a grasp; or P.
<ets>gripper</ets> to seize; -- of German origin. See <er>Gripe</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>To give a grip to; to grasp; to
gripe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grip car</ent>⟦br⟧
